<heading id="894481FBFFC7FFEBA1CB7DBD928B0D71" box="[194,747,1767,1792]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" reason="8">
FAMILY 
<taxonomicName id="15B34D14FFC7FFEBA0177DBD928B0D71" authority="YOUNG &amp; ROPER, 1968" authorityName="YOUNG &amp; ROPER" authorityYear="1968" box="[286,747,1767,1792]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Batoteuthidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oegopsida" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">
BATOTEUTHIDAE 
<bibRefCitation id="B6224B66FFC7FFEBA0ED7DBD928B0D71" author="Young RE &amp; Roper CFE" box="[484,747,1767,1792]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" pagination="185 - 202" refId="ref18107" refString="Young RE, Roper CFE. 1968. The Batoteuthidae, a new family of squid (Cephalopoda; Oegopsida) from Antarctic waters. Antarctic Research Series 2: 185 - 202." type="book chapter" year="1968">YOUNG &amp; ROPER, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D20C3697FFC7FFEBA08D7C5492490D56" blockId="14.[388,553,1806,1831]" box="[388,553,1806,1831]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226">(ONE SPECIES)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9AA9651CFFC7FFEBA1AA7C6D95F8087E" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D20C3697FFC7FFEBA1AA7C6D94110B27" blockId="14.[163,779,1846,1899]" lastBlockId="14.[827,1443,197,342]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226">
<emphasis id="E0C7EA85FFC7FFEBA1AA7C6D917B0D3D" box="[163,283,1847,1868]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Medium adult-sized 
<taxonomicName id="15B34D14FFC7FFEBA31D7C6C92AF0D3D" authorityName="GRAY" authorityYear="1849" box="[532,719,1846,1868]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Chiroteuthoidea">Chiroteuthoidea</taxonomicName>
with arm suckers in two series and tentacle suckers in six series, spanning 80% of tentacle length; photophores in aboral surface of ventral arm tips (large in males, small in females); distinctly curved funnel–mantle locking apparatus; long, unadorned tail supported by secondary conus of gladius.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D20C3697FFC7FFEBA2327A2495F8087E" blockId="14.[827,1443,382,527]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226">
<emphasis id="E0C7EA85FFC7FFEBA2327A2493C80BE2" box="[827,936,382,403]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226">Remarks:</emphasis>
Not included in our phylogenetic analyses, but its position within the superfamily is supported provisionally by its morphology (
<bibRefCitation id="B6224B66FFC7FFEBA5D67AE693120B81" author="Young RE &amp; Roper CFE" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" pagination="185 - 202" refId="ref18107" refString="Young RE, Roper CFE. 1968. The Batoteuthidae, a new family of squid (Cephalopoda; Oegopsida) from Antarctic waters. Antarctic Research Series 2: 185 - 202." type="book chapter" year="1968">Young &amp; Roper, 1968</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B6224B66FFC7FFEBA2777A8194C50B81" author="Vecchione M &amp; Young RE" box="[894,1189,474,496]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" refId="ref17571" refString="Vecchione M, Young RE. 2019 c. Neoteuthis thielei Naef, 1921. Version 26 March 2019 (under construction). Available at: http: // tolweb. org / Neoteuthis _ thielei / 19926 / 2019.03.26" type="url" year="2019">Young &amp; Vecchione, 2019c</bibRefCitation>
) and the phylogenetic results of 
<bibRefCitation id="B6224B66FFC7FFEBA2A27AA39402087E" author="Lindgren AR" box="[939,1122,505,527]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" pagination="77 - 90" refId="ref15706" refString="Lindgren AR. 2010. Molecular inference of phylogenetic relationships among Decapodiformes (Mollusca: Cephalopoda) with special focus on the squid Order Oegopsida. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 56: 77 - 90." type="journal article" year="2010">Lindgren (2010)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="B6224B66FFC7FFEBA5927AA395F1087E" author="Lindgren AR &amp; Pankey MS &amp; Hochberg FG &amp; Oakley TH" box="[1179,1425,505,527]" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226" pagination="129" refId="ref15774" refString="Lindgren AR, Pankey MS, Hochberg FG, Oakley TH. 2012. A multi-gene phylogeny of Cephalopoda supports convergent morphological evolution in association with multiple habitat shifts in the marine environment. BMC Evolutionary Biology 12: 129." type="journal article" year="2012">
Lindgren 
<emphasis id="E0C7EA85FFC7FFEBA4027AA09523087F" box="[1291,1347,505,527]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="1226">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
